[[File:Crowd-At-Hoppings-2006.jpg|thumb|The Hoppings in 2006]] '''The Hoppings''' is an annual [[travelling funfair]] held on the [[Town Moor, Newcastle upon Tyne|Town Moor]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], during the last week in June. It is one of [[Europe]]'s largest travelling funfairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/millions-go-hopping-mad-1588819.html |title=Millions go hopping mad |quote=Europe's largest travelling fair, the Hoppings, is a week of frenzied activity. |publisher=The Independent |date=29 June 1995 |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newcastle.gov.uk/news-story/plans-postpone-historic-hoppings |title=Plans to postpone historic Hoppings |date=15 March 2013 |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfa.dept.shef.ac.uk/history/charter/newcastle.html |title=Newcastle Town Moor Fair |publisher=National Fairground Archive |quote=In terms of size Newcastle is perhaps the biggest fair in Britain, if not in Europe |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> Its forerunner was The Blaydon Races, which was held in [[Blaydon]].{{citation-needed|date=March 2015}}
Several origins have been suggested for the name, most of which relate to dancing. The word “hopping”, means a dance in [[Middle English]] (Old fairs included dancing). Another idea stems from the clothing which the travellers used to wear; that being of old, sack-like tops and pants. Clothing often became infested with fleas from the animals that travelled with the fair. People were often seen “jumping” or “hopping” about itching from the bites which they received. Or the name may derive from the Anglo-Saxon word “hoppen” meaning funfair.
The fair began as a [[Temperance movement|Temperance Fair]] in 1882.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-40123610</ref> It was scheduled to coincide with Race Week at [[Newcastle Racecourse]], during which the ''[[Northumberland Plate]]'' was awarded.
[[File:The Hoppings, Newcastle Town Moor, 1960 (15399747002).jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the Hoppings in 1960]] The fair took place at [[Jesmond Dene]] from 1914–1918 and returned to the more spacious Town Moor, just north of the city centre, in 1919.{{citation-needed|date=March 2015}} There was no Festival on the Moor between 1920 and 1923, but it returned in June 1924, where it continued annually until 1946; a non-[[Showmen's Guild]] Fair was held that year but proved to be unpopular.{{citation-needed|date=March 2015}} The Guild showmen returned in 1947 and the Hoppings was a success with a record attendance.{{citation-needed|date=March 2015}}
The Hoppings inspired the song ''Katie Was There'' by [[Eric Boswell (songwriter)|Eric Boswell]] which was part of his 1983 musical ''[[Eric Boswell (songwriter)#Musical theatre: Catherine Cookson's "Katie Mulholland"|Katie Mulholland]]'', based on [[Catherine Cookson]]'s novel, staged by [[Northern_Stage,_Newcastle_upon_Tyne|Newcastle Playhouse]].
In 2013 after a dispute between the Showmen's Guild and Newcastle City Council over pitch and rent terms, alternate fairs were held at Nuns Moor Newcastle upon Tyne and [[Herrington|Herrington Country Park]], [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]].<ref>Lanagan, Paul; (2010). The Hoppings: Newcastle's Town Moor Fair. {{ISBN|978-0-9555059-0-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://m.sunderlandecho.com/what-s-on/sunderland-to-host-hoppings-style-funfair-after-newcastle-event-cancelled-1-5717181|title= Sunderland to host Hoppings–style funfair after Newcastle event cancelled|publisher=[[Sunderland Echo]] |date=2013-05-29 |accessdate=2013-06-12}}</ref> Newcastle council held an alternate event with “broader appeal” which included a funfair held on the Town Moor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-22167546 |title=Axed Newcastle Hoppings to be replaced by new community event |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=2013-04-16 |accessdate=2013-04-16}}</ref> The Hoppings returned to the Town Moor in 2014 after the dispute was resolved.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-26349671</ref>
[[File:Hoppings-2006.jpg|center|thumb|upright=3.0|Panorama of The Hoppings, 2006]]
